{{Infobox language |name=Lhao Vo |nativename=Lhao Vo |states=[[Myanmar]], [[China]] |speakers={{sigfig|103,500|2}} |date=1997 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=([[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman]]) |fam3=[[Lolo–Burmese languages|Lolo–Burmese]] |fam4=[[Burmish languages|Burmish]] |fam5=Maruic |iso3=mhx |glotto=maru1249 |glottorefname=Maru }}
'''Lhao Vo''', also known as '''Maru''' and '''Langsu''' ({{zh|浪速}}), is a [[Burmish language]] of Burma with a few thousand speakers in China.
==Distribution== Dai Qingxia (2005:3) reports 5,600 Langsu speakers in China. Many thousands more are dispersed across the eastern edge of [[Kachin State]], Burma. *[[Luxi City]]: Yingpan Township 营盘乡 *[[Lianghe County]]: Mengyang Township 勐养乡 *[[Longchuan County, Yunnan|Longchuan County]]: Bangwai Township 邦外乡 and Jingkan Township 景坎乡
The Langsu people call themselves ''lɔ̃˧˩ vɔ˧˩'' (Chinese: ''Lang'e'' 浪峨) (Dai 2003:3; Dai 2010:10)<ref>Dai Qingxia [戴庆厦] (2010). ''The Chashan people of Pianma and their language'' [片马茶山人及其语言]. Beijing: The Commercial Press [商务印书馆].</ref>
==Varieties== The standard Lhaovo dialect is that of the Dagoʔ (''tăkoʔ'') hill area, on the east side of [[N'Mai River]] valley in [[Kachin State]].<ref name="Sawada2017"/>
Sawada (2017) lists the following patois (subvarieties) of Lhaovo.<ref name="Sawada2017">Sawada, Hideo. 2017. ''Two Undescribed Dialects of Northern Burmish Sub-branch: Gyannoʔ and Thoʔlhang''. Presented at ICSTLL 50, Beijing, China.</ref> *'''Gyannoʔ''' (autonym: ''kjɛn35 noʔ21''): spoken in the west side of the N'Mai River in [[Sawlaw Township]]. *'''Thoʔlhang''' (autonym: ''tʰaʔ21 lo̰22''): spoken in [[Htawlang]] and a few other villages in northern Sawlaw Township. *'''Lakin''' (autonym: ''lăkɛ̰22''): spoken in [[Lakin, Burma|Lakin]] village, northern Sawlaw Township. *'''Lhangsu''' (autonym: ''la̰ŋ53 su53''; not the same as Langsu 浪速 of Yunnan): spoken in the area between Hkrang Hka and Sanin Hka, which are two tributaries of the Mali Hka. It is spoken in [[Sumprabum Township]], including in the villages of {{lang|ha|Hting Tsa, N-gawk Hkyet}}, and {{lang|ha|Ma Awng}}.
===Langsong=== The Langsong 浪宋 are found in Zaoyang 早阳<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vdefault.aspx?departmentid=60920</ref> in [[Yunlong County]] (in the Chinese province of [[Yunnan]]) as well as in Baocun 表村,<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=37739</ref> Laomo 老末, and Sancha 三岔.<ref>http://www.ynszxc.gov.cn/villagePage/vIndex.aspx?departmentid=37740</ref><ref>中国少数民族社会历史调查资料丛刊修订编辑委员会. 2009. 景颇族社会历史调查, p.57. Beijing: Minzu Chubanshe.</ref> They reportedly speak a highly endangered language that may be possibly related to Langsu.
